         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(the) god (of gods, he saw Bṛhaddyuti), the potter, having come with great joy, and immediately in order to evoke his great merits</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1952"/><citedRange>52</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #a6 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5 #b6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:sieg1944"/><citedRange>26</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:ogihara2010"/><citedRange>171-172</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">he stood there dressed with an upper garment like (a ... tree with a) liana. But how so? || In the Ṣ.-tune: || (Adorned with) the Cintāmaṇi</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>208</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... like an island of jewels decorated with jewels, magnificent, adorned with flowers, heavenly</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>19</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>204</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... like a golden tree adorned with lamps, like a divine pillar [made] of jewels he stood there</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>208</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1969"/><citedRange>249</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">adorned (with the 32 marks) [and] with the 80 ornaments. Like the sun, having produced a halo, surrounded by rays which are a fathom wide</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>788</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">..... the compassionate one. 1. Having seen that, Bṛhaddyuti (was) as if crushed by happiness and with wonder</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(he thought to himself): “As many things to be regarded as splendid as there are in the world, as many are (seen alive) on this body.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1 #b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1968"/><citedRange>228</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>104</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>71</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>102</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1997"/><citedRange>134</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... as in a heavenly mirror all forms. || In the S.-tune: || Former Buddhas and Pratyeka-</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2 txt:m-a23#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>23lf</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Frühere Buddhas [und] Pratyeka(buddhas, große Wei)se [und] Cakravartin-Könige, Ozean [und] See, Nāga-Könige, große Asuras ... (Viṣṇu [und] Mah)eśvara; Rosse, Fahrzeuge [und] Elefanten, die Yāma-, die Tuṣita- bis hin[auf] zur Śuddhāvāsa[-Götterwelt], [alle] glänzenden Dinge werden leibhaftig an diesem (buddhaschaftlichen) Körper gesehen.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">Earlier Buddhas [and] Pratyeka-(Buddhas, great wis)e ones [and] Cakravartin-kings, ocean [and] sea, Nāga-kings, great Asuras, ... (Viṣṇu [and] Mah)eśvara: horses, vehicles [and] elephants, the Yāma-, the Tuṣita- [and up] to the Śuddhāvāsa[-pantheon], [all] splendid things are to be seen incarnate on this (Buddha-like) body.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>231</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(buddhas, great) wise ones [and] Cakravartin-kings, ocean [and] sea, Nāga-kings, great Asuras,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... jeweled islands, ..., Cintāmaṇis, monasteries and residences of the communities, Dāna(śālas) [“halls of alms”]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... giving a gift. [1.]. The mountain of gods, Sumeru, the heavenly four kings [the guardians of the world], the Pārijāta-tree, Sudharmā [and] Vaijayanta [“Palaces of the gods”],</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Skandha, (Viṣṇu) [and] Maheśvara; horses, carts [and] elephants, the Yāma-, Tuṣita-,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6 txt:m-a23#a1"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>333</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>221</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice></p>
